Now, when I came in, I brought two years of experience with me, so I had a shorter time to make tenure, but I also brought articles I'd published and I had shared and I had some of those experiences, so I didn't figure I needed as much time.
What, as department head, did you have to determine salary increases and all that for your faculty?
Yes.
Do you have a set criteria, like all of the other departments, as to what people have to do to get tenure or to get promotion or to get the merit?
It's all merit.
Is it all merit?
Now, the tenure and promotion guidelines our department has just established, the faculty, we have a faculty committee of both tenure and untenured faculty worked on that.
They've set those.
As far as merit, we're working on that.
But I say we're working because when Ed Tech came in and we had to start all over again.
Because the guidelines we had with adult ed faculty I felt may or may not be appropriate.
So we're letting all faculty have input into this.
But these are guidelines that the faculty agreed to.
And we don't have points.
We don't say you've got to have so many publications or anything like that.
But we do have guidelines within which these increases.
I believe that every faculty member deserves some kind of a, at least a minimum raise.
From then on, then it becomes a merit.
Now, the dean appropriates each department with an X amount of dollars.
There's a number of dollars.
And it varies from department to department.
I assume, yes.
And then within that, you allocate that as you see fit.
But overall, the College of Education
faculty's salaries are not comparable to other colleges?
I don't think so.
No, I've never got the book out and looked at it.
But I had a faculty member do it two or three years ago.
He said we've got the lowest paid faculty.
And position by position, our assistant professors and associate and fulls are lower paid than most other colleges.
I think even liberal arts, I think we're lower.
What about when I hear from a couple of women that I've interviewed that
The women are not given enough opportunities in the College of Education for leadership.
For example, I think in the whole university, there's only one department head that's a female.
Do you get any pressure in the College of Education to hire more women or minorities or any of that?
Is there?
We get strong suggestions to hire minorities.
But of our five faculty in adult ed, three are female.
So I don't have any problem there.
Although I think the majority of our students are going to be female in the future if they aren't already, which I think is appropriate.
In Ed Tech, we only have one female faculty member because none apply.
We did offer a job last year to a female faculty member in Ed Tech, and she turned us down.
There wasn't enough money.
That's all the money we had.
And as far as leadership, I can assure you that none of the females in our department have won any leadership.
I've offered them leadership.
And they always say, no, we don't want it.
And one of them has a favorite saying, I'm not after anybody's job, so I enjoy my work.
I think one of them would be a good leader, but she just won't even consider it.
Are you willing to share the restructuring of EdTech coming into your department?
How did that come about?
All I know is the dean asked me to...
design a plan for that happening.
Nobody in our department asked for it to happen, and we're not disappointed that it happened.
They're good faculty.
But you'll have to ask the dean.
They're very autonomous, though.
I mean, it's pretty sad.
They're kind of doing a totally different...
They have their graduate study program.
They have a master's degree program, and they offer undergraduate courses to the college.
There's a coordinator, and...
They determine their own degree plans.
And they're very autonomous because there are certain things we do departmentally that we all do together.
But I know nothing about that area.
And those faculty make their own decisions.
Do you feel in the college that there is a great deal of autonomy?
For example, you as department head don't go around checking on your faculty where they are or what time or whether they're in classes or what their classes are doing.
Is it pretty once?
For example, how much autonomy do you have as a department head versus you or your faculty?
I think as a college, we're very autonomous.
I don't check on people unless I start getting complaints.
Then I start following up on it.
Otherwise, I don't worry about where my faculty are.
And then the dean doesn't actually dictate or specify or give you very, very set things to follow?
Not very often.
You pretty much can...
can do what you feel is necessary.
As long as we stay within the policies and procedures of the university.
Can you just tell me a couple or describe or something, elaborate or enlighten me about a policy committee meeting?
What exactly is it and what happens in these policy committee meetings?
They vary.
We usually under...
Under most conditions, we get a report as to what happened at the academic policies committees for the deans and deans of the colleges to give some idea of what's happening university-wide.
We get, I would say, soundings on problems that are university-wide that might affect the college.
If there's a decision to make on something that we have to do as a college, the dean usually asks the department how they want to go about doing it and what would be the best thing for us.
Dean's staff usually has some things to share with us on things that are going on, reports that are due, data that are due in, a lot of this kind of thing.
Sometimes we get into some very philosophic discussions about what the college ought to do.
There's never consensus, but there are disagreements, but they're usually followed up in a professional way, and everybody understands you can disagree and not worry about it.

But sometimes the dean suggests something, and occasionally, even though the department heads want it another way, the dean will say, I think this is what's in the best interest of the college, and here's the way it's going to be.
I have heard that department heads are not given an opportunity to meet apart from the dean's staff.
If you wanted to, could you, or have you ever?
It's interesting.
About three years ago, I started a luncheon meeting of all department heads in the college.
I called one.

set it up invited everybody came we had lunch and we sat around and talked for about an hour everybody agreed we ought to do it again and i said okay it's somebody else's turn to set it up and we've never met since i refuse to set them up all the time but you can if you want to know there's no policy just in fact uh this last year uh dr phillips dean of faculty met with all department heads in groups of about
seven or eight from different colleges over lunch and had some excellent discussions.
And I understand there's supposed to be a department heads council developed.
What do you think about the faculty senate and what has evolved out of that?
I think it's a good thing.
I don't agree with all their decisions, but I think it's a good thing.
And I think faculty ought to have input.
Did that come from the president?
Was that initiated by the president?
The president supported it.
It came from some faculty.
got together and initiated.
OK, the last thing I'm going to ask you is about the Development Council, because you have been actively involved with the Development Council since the beginning.
Tell me a little bit about where you think it's going or what your perceptions are.
There's a little bit of change in focus.
For a long time, it was all of the department heads lining up and getting up and giving a report and sitting down.
And now the focus is kind of changing a little bit.
And we're trying to get more work out
Development Council.
But I'm hearing that the Development Council doesn't have direction as to where they're going to go.
It started out as it was just going to be advisory.
Now it's because of the challenge of the provost that this last Development Council joined the faculty meeting of the 150,000.
There's a more thrust to fundraising.
How do you feel about all of that?
Well, I think the Development Council ought to be a working council.
We need your advice, definitely, but I think you ought to be working.
Fundraising may be part of it, recruiting, possibly identifying programs or places where the faculty or departments can become involved in that kind of thing.
I also believe that for years, the council really didn't accomplish too much.
But I don't think it's the council's fault.
I don't think they were given much to do.
And if there's going to be a change of direction now with specific things they can work on, I think it'll be good.
As far as department heads' reports, I don't think the department heads wanted to give them, nor I don't think the council wanted to hear them.
I got that feeling from everybody.
So I think the council would be better off meeting and working.
If they need a department head or two, call them in and ask them, talk to them.
But don't have all these people sitting around and... Now that they're...
Breaking into committees, your interest on adult literacy is one of the areas that they want to work in.
Do you perceive being able to work for things that the council will be able to help you with?
I hope so, but I wasn't at the last meeting because of a conflict, and I don't know what happened and haven't been given any report yet, so I'm still waiting for that.
Okay.
Well, Dr.
Seaman, I want to thank you for sharing so many insights, and I appreciate your input.
And if you have any...
documents or things that you run across that would give me some extra ideas or some things to verify what I've been getting, I would appreciate it.
And if I have some questions down the road after I start trying to put it all together, I hope you'll let me come back and ask you a couple of more questions.
You know my telephone number.
